The usually rather boring area of road planning has suddenly sparked an intense debate with colorful alliances.
Libertaries have allied themselves with environmental groups and call for the government to be able to use the small boxes to record the kilometres used – and perhaps where they have been driven – and then use the information to calculate tax decisions.
The Tea Party is appalled.
The United States Civil Rights Association (ACLU) is also deeply concerned and expresses a number of data protection concerns.
But, while Congress cannot agree, several states are no longer waiting.
