But the Republican Bill Shuster of Pennsylvania, Chairman of the House Transportation Committee, has also declared that he sees this as the most viable long-term alternative.
The free marketers of the Reason Foundation are also impressed by the idea of having drivers pay after the distance they have travelled.
“ This is not a tax that disappears in a black hole, ” explains Adrian Moore, Vice President for Guidelines at Reason.
People pay for what they get.
The movement is also supported by two former US Secretary of Transport who, in a 2011 report, called on Congress to move towards mileage reckoning.
Last year, the US Senate approved a $90 million pilot project worth $10,000 cars.
But the majority in the House of Representatives prevented progress from being made, in response to the concerns of rural MEPs who represent people who often have to travel many miles on their way to work or the city in their daily lives.
Nevertheless, several states and cities are moving in this direction on their own.
The most committed one is Oregon, who is currently recruiting 5,000 drivers for the country ’ s largest experiment.
