There is no need to build a gigantic, bulky technological infrastructure that would inevitably be used to collect data on the daily movements of individuals.
Nevada is one of a series of states that are now looking for affordable technology to help the state capture the kilometers they travel, but not exactly when and where.
According to Khan, this would also reassure the public.
The hunt for this technology has led to a small start-up company called True Mileage in California.
The company did not originally set up to help states tax drivers.
Rather, their aim was to gain a foothold in an emerging market for motor insurance, with drivers paying on the basis of the miles taken.
But the devices she tested are also interesting for road planners, because they do not work with GPS and provide limited information that is regularly uploaded via modem.
