Esa decides on major space missions: missions for billions
Far planets, gravitational waves or black holes - Experts from the European Space Agency must now agree on two major projects that they intend to launch in the coming years.
There were 30 proposals to choose from, and five are still in the race.
Far away worlds.
Astronomers have found more than 1000 planets at other stars.
No one knows whether there are at least some of them.
It is difficult to choose: are we to search for gravitational waves?
Or rather explore the origin of the cosmos?
Or search for earth-like planets and thus thus perhaps discover extratraterrestrial life?
These are the questions that those responsible for the European Space Agency, Esa, are asking.
For their Cosmic Vision programme, they are looking for ideas for two major space projects that should make decisive progress in research.
The budget for such' L missions' is around EUR 1 billion each.
Start is expected in 2028 and 2034.
In early September, the European space research elite met in Paris to discuss proposals for such missions.
Thirty ideas were under discussion, five of which have now been shortlisted.
Many bodies examine the proposals and hurt researchers.
A final decision is to be taken in the next few days by the Scientific Programme Committee.
A total of four major questions have been selected by Esa, to which the missions of the 2007 Cosmic Vision program will find answers.
What are the conditions for the emergence of planets and life?
The exact processes of the formation of stars from large gas clouds - and thus the emergence of the planets surrounding these stars - are still in proverbial darkness.
A large infrared telescope in space could penetrate this darkness.
And if a star possesses a planet, under what circumstances can life arise there?
In 2017, the space telescope " Cheops " is to be launched to investigate this issue, which will take a closer look at 500 already known planetary systems in our vicinity.
The possibilities are limited, however, and Cheops is a small mission with a budget of EUR 150 million.
With larger instruments, astronomers could map earth-like planets and even analyze the composition of their atmospheres, thus searching for " biomarkers ": gases considered an indication of biological activity.
How does the solar system work?
This issue, too, should ultimately ultimately shed light on the preconditions for the emergence of life.
An important role is played by the magnetic activity of a star and the interaction of its magnetic field, as well as the particle radiation it emits with the planetary system.
In our solar system, these processes can be examined as an example.
With the " Solar Orbiter ", the Esa has already approved an M class mission (where the budget is about half a billion euros) for this issue.
The probe is to start in 2017 and closely monitor the surface and activity of the sun.
Jupiter and his moons are also of great interest to researchers.
They want to find out what role the giant planet has played in developing the solar system.
The Esa is the first of the three L missions of the Cosmic Vision program.
The probe " Juice " (Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer) is expected to begin its journey in 2022.
Eight years later, it reached Jupiter and would examine the atmosphere of the planet and the icy moons of Europe, Kallisto and Ganymed.
What are the basic universe physical laws?
Space offers many opportunities to study matter under extreme conditions and thus to examine whether the laws of nature that we know are still valid there.
Perhaps there are also deviations that could show physicists the way to a new theory under whose umbrella all known laws of nature can be combined.
How did the universe come into being and what does it consist of?
Our cosmos were created by the big bang 13.7 billion years ago.
In addition to the familiar matter that consists of stars, planets, and creatures like us, there is dark matter whose gravity holds galaxies and clusters of galaxies, and dark energy whose action accelerates the expansion of space.
So far, researchers do not know which physical laws were valid in the first fraction of a second of the Big Bang, nor do they know what dark matter and dark energy consist of.
With Euclid, the Esa has already approved an M mission, which is scheduled for launch in 2020.
With a special telescope, the probe is intended to examine the distribution of matter in the universe for the first time in the entire sky, thus enabling conclusions to be drawn as to the nature of dark matter and dark energy.
Who Could Do the Race
Of the 30 proposals, only two will be left over at the end of the selection process.
In the opinion of many experts, the best chance of being approved as an L mission is " E-Lisa ", an ambitious concept for proving gravitational waves.
By this, physicists mean changes in the structure of spacetime, which Albert Einstein predicted almost 100 years ago.
They have not been proven to date.
Elisa could, scientists behind the project hope.
The mission provides for one of two or three probes stationed in space.
In contrast to installations on Earth, it could also detect the gravitational waves that emerged during the Big Bang, thus providing new insights into the formation of the cosmos.
Four other proposals compete for the second L mission: a large X-ray telescope called " Athena " to explore black holes, " Icy Planets ", another mission to the solar system's outer planets, " Prism ", a mission measuring cosmic background radiation, and the " Exoplanet Finder " to detect and investigate earth-like planets.
Proposals have already been made for sample transport from Mars, research into the moon, Venus and asteroids as well as solar physics.
