What happens to my email on the way?
E-mail is actually electronic.
Has the design of the Internet service e-mail technically implemented the technical recrecy of letters, as in the case of conventional postal services?
The main focus of the conception of the early Internet services was to make communication possible.
That is why the basic technical protocols have not failed to provide a solid foundation for audible correspondence.
As a result, a conventional e-mail is an open postcard rather than a sealed letter.
When the user " Anna " sends a mail to " Benni ", are the computers of the two directly connected?
The e-mail program or browser of Anna sends the mail to her service provider's mail server in the first step.
For example, if she has a GMaMail account, that would be Google.
This mail server sends the content to the provider using Benni.
On the route, the mail can run via a number of other servers on the Internet.
Bennie can then call the content from its provider.
Are conventional e-mails read on their way through the net?
Most of the mails are read several times on the way by software robots.
The sender's provider usually checks whether the mail has a malicious program as an attachment.
A virus check is also carried out on the receiver systems.
In addition, the providers check whether it is an annoying and unsolicited spam mail that is immediately immediately or at least sorted away into a spam folder.
Do robots have another task?
On systems such as GMail, the robot also detects the information Google needs to place context advertising.
If Anna and Benni communicate by GMail about their upcoming holiday trip, Google can display the corresponding links to holiday offerings.
Also unknown people read the e-mails?
There is very little likelihood that unauthorised persons will read a mail.
However, this is possible in theory.
In companies, administrators often have the opportunity to read electronic mail.
The law enforcement authorities and the secret services also have legal opportunities to intercept or take note of e-mails.
In addition, there are possible illegal spying actions.
Is it possible to protect e-mails against reading?
An OpenPGP standard encryption can be used to encrypt an e-mail against reading.
With a lot of technical effort, it is also possible to conceal the metadata of an e-mail communication, so that it is not easy to identify who has communicated with whom.
