An interesting point is lost in the constant repetition of this ancient story.
Why expect an independent Scotland to dance to the European pipe?
Why exchange the London yoke for Brussels, especially now?
This is the real European news: the great post-war plan for the unification of Europe has stalled.
With the euro crisis, the European project has officially died.
Parties across the EU that are hostile to the EU or want to throw the euro overboard as a single currency are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the Euroskeptic Alternative Party for Germany – founded only this year – was able to win just under five million votes in September ’ s federal election, effectively evicing the Free Democrats (the equivalent of the British Liberal Democrats) out of the Bundestag.
There has always been domestic opposition to the plan to create a federalist Europe.
The current economic crisis, however, is proving to be a turning point.
Many people believe that the European project has gone too far because of the strict austerity policies imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, combined with the straitjacket into which the national economy is being coerced by adherence to the single currency.
The euro ’ s crisis has little to do with national governments causing excessive budget deficits – only in Greece.
Instead, the Eurosystem has nailed its members on exchange rates that are beneficial to German exporters – and that is what German policymakers would like.
Without the possibility of devaluing the local currency, southern Europe will find itself at a built-in productivity disadvantage vis-à-vis Germany.
The only way is to cut wages and public spending – spurred on by Berlin.
Behind the current budget and currency problems, there is a deeper European productivity problem.
As a result of the “ green ” energy policies prescribed by Brussels – a code to subsidize French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers – European industry pays twice for electricity and four times for gas compared to the United States.
This is a paralysing cost disadvantage, as we saw in Grangemouth.
All wage definitions in the world do not protect the European petrochemical industry from being marginalised by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, a revolt, especially in France, the former EU cheerleader.
After the war, France ’ s political elite saw the EU as a vehicle that could keep Germany at bay and put Paris on an equal footing with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a gateway to political legitimacy, and has imposed its own economic policy on Europe, which is what the battered French economy is struggling with.
The result: Marine Le Pen ’ s more right-wing, anti-EU National Front has just won a decisive re-election, putting the ruling socialists in third place.
The National Front is now the most popular party in France, with 24% of the vote – a timely warning to the British Labour Party that it cannot assume that right-wing divisions will automatically benefit the left.
What is Le Pen doing with her newfound popularity among white working-class French?
It wants to use next year's EU elections to forge an anti-EU anti-Community currency bloc in the European Parliament.
If the anti-EU parties do well in these elections – and this is very well possible – then for the first time such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament.
This is the point I would like to focus on: in the not-too-distant future, the growing resentment of the EU and the single currency will come together to abolish the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will become something of the “ Europe of (sovereign) nations ” that General de Gaulle favored.
Germany and some of its satellite economies may be sticking to the euro, but France and southern Europe will return to their own currencies.
I expect Britain to distance itself from this project in the hope of flattering itself with the United States.
But Washington ’ s growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will be in Atlantic rain alone.
Where is Scotland in all this?
We can decide to be a region of (in the final analysis) Lesser England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests – including telling Berlin and Brussels what they can do.
I suspect Scotland could do well in a looser European union if we keep our own currency.
Cooperation with other similar countries is easier in a non-federal Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider doing the same Norway and maintaining our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is – remarkably, the most successful anti-austerity political movement in Europe, winning a spectacular majority in 2011 by rejecting the proposed (and made) cuts for which Labour Finance Minister Alistair Darling and the successive Tory Lib Dems coalition were responsible.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to opt for independence now, only to have an austerity policy imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
