They measured the heart rate of four-legged and analyzed behavior.
We will probably soon understand why the tail is moving in one direction or the other.
Professor Vallortigara said, “ We have shown the dogs films with dogs – either a faithful version or a silhouette to eliminate distracting other aspects, and we have been able to steer the movement of the tail more to the left or to the right. ”
When the animals saw how an otherwise expressive dog moved the tail to the right (seen from the perspective of the waving dog), they remained completely relaxed.
But if the tail inclination was mainly to the left (again from the perspective of the dog that wings), their heart rate rose and they looked restless.
According to Professor Vallortigara, the dogs do not deliberately communicate through these movements.
Rather, he is convinced that the dogs would have learned from experience which movements they should and should not worry about.
He said, “ If you have different encounters with other dogs and swing with the tail in one direction is more associated to friendly behavior, and if the right tends to produce less friendly behavior, you react on the basis of these experiences. ”
Researchers say that the findings could help dog owners, veterinary surgeons and trainers better understand the emotions of their animals.
John Bradshaw, an expert on dog behaviour and guest scholarship at the Faculty of Animal Medicine at the University of Bristol, said that this was not the first study examining whether dogs were important on the left and right.
