For 21 years, Georges Bwelle saw his sick father lose consciousness and travel to hospitals that did not have the means to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon in 1981.
At first he had only one broken arm, but then an inflammation spread to his brain, causing a haematomas to affect him for the rest of his life.
“ There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon, ” Georges Bwelle.
We would have released it from Cameroon if we had had the money.
Instead, Bwelle spent years accompanying his father to overcrowded clinics and hospitals to get the treatment they had to offer.
“ It ’ s not easy, ” comments Bwelle.
You can leave the house at five o'clock in the morning and run to the hospital to be the first, and you are not the first.
There are many patients.
Some people even die because they have to wait.
The situation has scarcely changed since Bwell ’ s father died in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only one doctor for 5,000 people each, according to the World Health Organisation.
In the United States, on the other hand, the ratio lies with a doctor for 413 people.
But even if there were a doctor for them, most cameroons could not afford to visit them.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of domestic health expenditures are private.
“ The only problem they have is poverty, ” says Bwelle.
Poverty makes it impossible to enjoy life.
To see his father and so many of his compatriots suffer made Bwelle decide to do something about it.
Dr Georges Bwelle and his voluntary team carried out 700 free operations last year.
He became a doctor and worked as a vascular surgeon at the Central Hospital in Yaoundé.
He also founded a non-profit organization called ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas at weekends and provides free medical care there.
Since 2008, he and his voluntary group have helped just under 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 people forced themselves on minibuses and ride with the snowed medical equipment on the roof over unpaved terrain to the villages that need help.
Not always smoothly.
On more than one occasion, they have had to push the vehicles by means of rivers and sludge.
But when they arrive, they are received like heroes: a feast, singing and dance, and the best accommodation the place has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care really is a cause for celebration and wave – with its broad smile and unlimited energy – is part at the happy celebration.
The next morning, the team will start the examination of hundreds of patients.
“ We treat 500 people per journey, ” says Bwelle.
They come from a radius of 60 kilometres around the village – and on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics provides healthcare in a number of areas.
Many people are treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others receive crutches, donated glasses, or free birth certificates – a document that is needed for school but that many poor families simply cannot afford.
In the evening, the team performs simple operations with local anaesthesia.
The operations usually take place in a school, the town hall or an apartment; after the operation, the patients get up and go to the recreation area to make room for the next.
The lighting for the surgical and disinfection equipment is fed by the group generator, so Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of Sunday.
It ’ s a strenuous pensum, but the village musicians usually help to keep the team motivated.
“ They drum all night so that we can stay awake and continue our work, ” says Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team goes back to the city, tired but proud of the work that has been done.
The group – a mixture of Cameroon doctors and foreign medical students – carried out 700 free operations over the past year, and knows that its work makes a huge difference for the people it helps.
One man explained that the free operation of a break he received now allowed him to work again.
“ That changes the future of my family, ” the man said.
Besides the weekend clinics and his work as a surgeon in the hospital, Bwelle also works in private clinics in Yaoundé at night.
With this second job, he finances 60% of his non-profit activities, according to Bwelle; the rest comes from private donations.
“ I really don't t know when he ’ slesleeping, ” says Katie O'Malley, who is studying medicine at Drexel University in Philadelphia in the second year and volunteering into Bwell's group.
He is always either in hospital or tempted to raise money for the organisation so that he can go to these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O'Malley, who come from the US and Europe and support Bwelle, this is an opportunity to gain practical experience that they would never get at home.
“ We can be involved in operations where we help extract blood or consider the instruments to be Dr. Bwelle, ” explains O'Malley.
This would never be possible in America as a medical student in the second year.
The students usually pay for their journey to Cameroon themselves and often bring with them donated sanitary equipment.
Once they are in Yaoundé, Bwelle will provide accommodation, transport and guidance.
“ He is undoubtedly a hero, ” says O'Malley.
He dedicates his life to this organisation and his desire to help the Cameroon people knows no bounds.
Almost permanent work is not a burden on wave.
It gives him great pleasure to make others happhappier and thereby fulfilling a promise he made to his father.
“ I am so happy with this work, ” Bwelle says.
And remember my father.
I hope he sees what I do.
I do it to make people laugh again and to relieve the pain.
