Tourism: Descent to Romans
A sewage channel from the Roman period has been preserved beneath Cologne at a length of about 120 metres.
If you visit Cologne, you can't miss the cathedral.
The two towers rise about 157 metres and make it the second highest church building in Europe.
Few visitors who admire the two delicate church towers can imagine that there is also a lot to discover beneath the cathedral.
Rainer Schulze is an expert in the underworld of Cologne.
The meeting point for his guided tours is the Service Centre of Köln-Tourismus right next to the cathedral.
The tour starts unspectacular: " We start in the underground garage, " says Schulze.
In the seventies, the fathers of the city wanted a decent city, and that is why only what was not too large stopped from the remains of the old city wall.
Most users of the multi-storey car park are therefore rushing past the Roman remains and only parking their cars.
However, if you take a closer look, you will find an archaeological site in the Parkdeck D2, separated by metal grids.
You can see about five metre high ruins made of hand-held sized stones.
" They are the remains of the Roman city wall built in the second half of the first century B.C., " says Schulze.
Before it comes back to light, Schulze lets the participants on the upper level of the park take a look at a dark 15 meter deep shaft.
This is the well of the old cathedral, which, unfortunately, is hardly noticed either.
Nearby stop of the tour is the pretorium, and here the participants descend again.
This is the seat of once the most powerful man north of the Alps, the preactor of CCAA.
A visitor would like to know what CCAA means.
" The abbreviation stands for " Colonia Claudia Ara Agrippinensium ", which in good German means as much as " City of Roman Law and the City of the Agrippinensers, founded under Emperor Claudius at the place of the altar for the imperial cult ".
The pretorium is the former palace, the centre of power of the Roman Empire on the Rhine.
A tunnel leads from the anteroom of the exhibition to the Roman sewage canal, which is preserved here at about 120 metres in length.
" You can walk a bit along the so-called Cloaca Maxima if you like, " Schulze encourages guests.
A surprise still exists.
After getting the key at the box office, he leads the group to a 16 metre deep, walkable shaft.
" We are now in Mikwe, a ritual Jewish bath, " he explains.
The Jewish community built its bath deep into the ground to obtain the groundwater that was essential for ritual washing.
To this day in the lower end of the Mikwe, whose origins date back to the eighth century, different water levels can be read by changing levels of the Rhine.
The Mikwe will be part of an archaeological area on the Town Hall Square, for which construction work is due to begin shortly.
However, it will be a few years before it is completed.
